---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Heading from "../../components/Heading.astro";
import Highlight from "../../components/Highlight.astro";
import PageHeader from "../../components/PageHeader.astro";
import Paragraph from "../../components/Paragraph.astro";
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import ImageStep3a from "../../images/portfolio/design-system-ux/step3a.png";
import ImageStep3b from "../../images/portfolio/design-system-ux/step3b.png";
import ImageStep3c from "../../images/portfolio/design-system-ux/step3c.png";
import ImageStep3d from "../../images/portfolio/design-system-ux/step3d.png";
import ImageStep3e from "../../images/portfolio/design-system-ux/step3e.png";
import ImageStep3f from "../../images/portfolio/design-system-ux/step3f.png";
import ImageStep3g from "../../images/portfolio/design-system-ux/step3g.png";
import ImageStep3h from "../../images/portfolio/design-system-ux/step3h.png";
import ImageWrapper from "../../components/ImageWrapper.astro";
import HighlightAndImageItem from "../../layouts/HighlightAndImageItem.astro";
import HorizontalScrollList from "../../layouts/HorizontalScrollList.astro";
import HorizontalScrollItem from "../../layouts/HorizontalScrollItem.astro";
import HighlightAndImageList from "../../layouts/HighlightAndImageList.astro";
import Prose from "../../layouts/Prose.astro";
import BackToPortfolio from "../../components/BackToPortfolio.astro";
const title = "Improving a design system’s UX";
---

<BaseLayout pageTitle={title}>
  <BackToPortfolio />
  <PageHeader heading={title}>
    The goal of this project was to evaluate and improve the UX of the design
    system I was working on. The project focused on the design system’s two main
    user groups: designers and developers. There was most room for improvement
    with regards to the UX of designers, so that’s what I’ve chosen to focus on
    here.
  </PageHeader>
  <Prose>
    <Heading as="h2" step="1">Quantitative research</Heading>
    <Paragraph>
      My first step was to send out an anonymous survey to all product
      designers.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
      The aim was to find out whether the design system was living up to key
      objectives across various areas.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
      The survey consisted of 17 questions across five categories. Most were
      phrased as statements. The designers were asked to specify on a five-point
      scale to what degree they agreed or disagreed with the statements. Here
      are example statements from the different categories:
    </Paragraph>
    <HorizontalScrollList>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight title="General" blockquote icon="questionMark">
          It's clear what the design system’s single source of truth is, when it
          comes to components, design tokens, guidelines, etc.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight
          title="Finding and using components"
          blockquote
          icon="search"
        >
          It's clear what to do when a component doesn't exist or doesn't meet
          all my requirements.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight title="Contributing" blockquote icon="add">
          I feel welcome to contribute new or improved components.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight title="Help and communication" blockquote icon="support">
          The design system team replies to questions and comments in a clear
          and helpful way.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight title="How can we do better?" blockquote icon="trendingUp">
          What's the most important thing the design system team should do
          differently?
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
    </HorizontalScrollList>
    <Heading as="h2" step="2">Qualitative research</Heading>
    <Paragraph>
      My second step was to interview every designer about the results of the
      survey.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
      The goal was to get more detailed insight into the discovered issues.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
      The main questions I asked for every issue, can be seen here. To get a
      more complete picture, I also asked more general questions about their
      experiences with the design system.
    </Paragraph>
    <HorizontalScrollList>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight title="Have you experienced this issue?" icon="check">
          The survey’s results showed that the designers didn’t always agree on
          whether the design system was achieving a certain key objective or
          not. As a result, for every discovered issue, I had to check whether
          the designer I was interviewing actually agreed it was an issue for
          them.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight
          title="How and when does the issue impact your work?"
          icon="work"
        >
          The aim of this question was to better understand how the design
          system was failing to achieve a certain key objective within the
          context of a designer’s daily work.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight title="How can we do better?" icon="trendingUp">
          I had some ideas about how to tackle the discovered issues. However, I
          was curious to hear what the designers thought would be the best
          approach. They provided me with great input and helpful suggestions.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
    </HorizontalScrollList>
    <Heading as="h2" step="3">Implement changes</Heading>
    <Heading as="h3">Make documentation site more designer oriented</Heading>
    <Paragraph>
      A main finding was that the design system’s documentation site was too
      focused on developers.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
      Designers felt like much of the content was too technical and they had
      difficulty finding information that was relevant to them.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
      Several changes were made to the documentation site to address this issue.
      Some of these changes are highlighted here.
    </Paragraph>
    <HighlightAndImageList>
      <HighlightAndImageItem>
        <Highlight
          slot="highlight"
          title="Role-specific guideline sections"
          headingLevel="h4"
          icon="groups"
        >
          Before, guidelines for developers, designers, and UX writers could be
          found in a single section called “Guidelines”. Now, this section is
          split up into role-specific “Developing”, “Writing”, and “Designing”
          sections.
        </Highlight>
        <ImageWrapper slot="image">
          <Image
            src={ImageStep3a}
            alt="The main navigation of the design system’s documentation site. It features role-specific sections labelled “Developing”, “Writing”, and “Designing”."
            width="400"
            densities={[2, 3, 4]}
          />
        </ImageWrapper>
      </HighlightAndImageItem>
      <HighlightAndImageItem>
        <Highlight
          slot="highlight"
          title="Icons FAQ"
          headingLevel="h4"
          icon="qa"
        >
          A up-to-date and single-source of truth for guidelines about how to
          work with icons had always been missing. To address this issue, I
          created an “Icons FAQ” page and added it to the “Designing” section.
        </Highlight>
        <ImageWrapper slot="image">
          <Image
            src={ImageStep3b}
            alt="The “Icons FAQ” page  of the design system’s documentation site. It features questions, such as “I need an icon. How do I check whether it exists in Fancy?”."
            width="1000"
            densities={[2, 3, 4]}
          />
        </ImageWrapper>
      </HighlightAndImageItem>
      <HighlightAndImageItem>
        <Highlight
          slot="highlight"
          title="Accessibility checklist for designers"
          headingLevel="h4"
          icon="checklist"
        >
          Enabling designers to create accessible user experiences is one of the
          design system’s main goals. However, the documentation site was
          missing accessibility guidelines concerning UI design. I collaborated
          with accessibility experts to create a checklist specifically for
          designers.
        </Highlight>
        <ImageWrapper slot="image">
          <Image
            src={ImageStep3c}
            alt="An accessibility guideline from the design system’s documentation site. The guideline is in a “Do Don’t” format that explains how screen reader users experience pages in a linear fashion."
            width="1000"
            densities={[2, 3, 4]}
          />
        </ImageWrapper>
      </HighlightAndImageItem>
      <HighlightAndImageItem>
        <Highlight
          slot="highlight"
          title="Improve icons overview page"
          headingLevel="h4"
          icon="grid"
        >
          The icons overview page was cluttered, making it difficult for
          designers to scan the page and find the icon they were looking for. I
          cleaned up the page and added a link to the new “Icons FAQ” page.
        </Highlight>
        <ImageWrapper slot="image">
          <Image
            src={ImageStep3d}
            alt="The “Icons Overview” page of the design system’s documentation site. It features a grid of icons and a link to the “Icons FAQ” page."
            width="1000"
            densities={[2, 3, 4]}
          />
        </ImageWrapper>
      </HighlightAndImageItem>
    </HighlightAndImageList>
    <Heading as="h3">Clarify single source of truth</Heading>
    <Paragraph>
      The research also revealed it was sometimes unclear for designers what the
      single source of truth was, when it came to component documentation,
      guidelines, design tokens, etc.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
      Here you can see some of the actions that were taken to solidify the
      documentation site as the one and only source of truth.
    </Paragraph>
    <HorizontalScrollList>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight
          title="Add warnings to deprecated pages"
          headingLevel="h4"
          icon="warning"
        >
          Some deprecated documentation pages could not be removed, due to still
          being relevant for internal use in the design system team. Warning
          messages were added to prevent designers from consulting these pages.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight
          title="Shorten and simplify documentation URL"
          headingLevel="h4"
          icon="link"
        >
          The documentation site is the design system’s official single source
          of truth. However, its URL was quite long and difficult to remember.
          Therefore, it was simplified and shortened to fancy.siteimprove.com.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight
          title="Move guidelines to documentation site"
          headingLevel="h4"
          icon="public"
        >
          Some documentation could only be found outside of the official
          documentation site. That helps explain the designers’ confusion with
          regards to the true single source of truth. Documentation that was
          still relevant and up-to-date was moved to the documentation site.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
    </HorizontalScrollList>
    <ImageWrapper>
      <Image
        src={ImageStep3e}
        alt="A partially yellow warning message informing the reader that the components on the page are from the previous version of the design system, that the page is only intended for internal use by the design system team, and that they should visit the official documentation site instead for up-to-date component documentation."
        width="480"
        densities={[2, 3, 4]}
      />
    </ImageWrapper>
    <Heading as="h3">Clarify terminology and processes</Heading>
    <Paragraph>
      Another main finding was that certain terminology and processes for
      working with the design system were unclear to some designers.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
      These terms and processes had been explained informally on multiple
      occasions. However, they had never been collected in a central, easily
      accessible location.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
      I added a general FAQ for designers to the documentation site to create
      such a knowledge repository.
    </Paragraph>
    <ImageWrapper>
      <Image
        src={ImageStep3f}
        alt="The “General FAQ for designers” page of the design system’s documentation site. It features questions divided into sections labelled “General”, “Components”, and “Process”."
        width="640"
        densities={[2, 3, 4]}
      />
    </ImageWrapper>
    <Heading as="h3">Keep designers up-to-date</Heading>
    <Paragraph>
      During the interviews, several designers expressed a desire to be kept
      more up-to-date about the latest changes and additions to the design
      system.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
      Two initiatives were started to accommodate this request.
    </Paragraph>
    <HighlightAndImageList>
      <HighlightAndImageItem>
        <Highlight
          slot="highlight"
          title="Changelogs"
          headingLevel="h4"
          icon="history"
        >
          Public changelogs were added to the documentation site. The changelogs
          are written in a manner intended to be understandable to a
          non-technical audience.
        </Highlight>
        <ImageWrapper slot="image">
          <Image
            src={ImageStep3g}
            alt="The “Changelog” page of the design system’s documentation site. It features a chronologically ordered list of version updates with non-technical descriptions of the included changes."
            width="640"
            densities={[2, 3, 4]}
          />
        </ImageWrapper>
      </HighlightAndImageItem>
      <HighlightAndImageItem>
        <Highlight
          slot="highlight"
          title="More frequent updates"
          headingLevel="h4"
          icon="news"
        >
          News about the design system is now posted about more frequently in a
          Slack channel specifically for designers.
        </Highlight>
        <ImageWrapper slot="image">
          <Image
            src={ImageStep3h}
            alt="A Slack message from Hans Sandberg containing a bullet point list of design system updates with various positive emoji reactions, such as raised hands."
            width="640"
            densities={[2, 3, 4]}
          />
        </ImageWrapper>
      </HighlightAndImageItem>
    </HighlightAndImageList>
    <Heading as="h3">Improve review process</Heading>
    <Paragraph>
      The interviews revealed it was unclear to designers how and when to get
      their wireframes and mockups reviewed by the design system team.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
      I discussed different options with the designers, to see what suited their
      needs best. This collaborative effort resulted in a proposal for a new
      review session format. Key characteristics of this new format are
      described here.
    </Paragraph>
    <HorizontalScrollList>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight
          title="Multi-disciplinary feedback"
          headingLevel="h4"
          icon="groups"
        >
          In the new review sessions, designers can receive feedback from the
          design system team, accessibility experts, and UX writers
          simultaneously. This eleminates the need for separate sessions and
          allows prompt resolution of conflicting feedback.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight
          title="Open for all designers"
          headingLevel="h4"
          icon="meetingRoom"
        >
          Designers wanted to attend their fellow designers' review sessions to
          learn from the feedback and offer input from a UX perspective. This
          would enhance the overall feedback culture in the UX team.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight
          title="Optional and informal"
          headingLevel="h4"
          icon="coffee"
        >
          Designers did not want the review sessions to be mandatory. They were
          concerned about excessive feedback and formality. To address this, It
          was decided to highlight the sessions as optional and an efficient way
          to gather feedback from diverse disciplines.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
    </HorizontalScrollList>
    <Heading as="h2" step="4">Presentation</Heading>
    <Paragraph>
      The last step was to give a presentation to the designers.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
      This presentation served multiple purposes, highlighted here.
    </Paragraph>
    <HorizontalScrollList>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight title="Show appreciation" icon="heart">
          First of all, I wanted to thank the designers for their participation
          in the project. They had invested significant time filling out the
          survey and being interviewed, which I wanted to show my appreciation
          for.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight title="Share findings and changes" icon="share">
          Secondly, I wanted the designers to know, that their time was well
          spent. To that end, I reiterated the project’s purpose, shared the
          most important findings, and showcased both the implemented and
          planned changes.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight title="Request feedback" icon="feedback">
          I was also curious to hear what the designers thought of the project
          and especially the implemented and planned changes. Thankfully, their
          initial reactions were positive.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight title="Announce reoccurrence" icon="repeat">
          Lastly, wanted to announce that this wasn’t the first and last project
          of its kind. The plan is to conduct a similar project every year. This
          way, the design system will iteratively become better at serving its
          users.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
    </HorizontalScrollList>
  </Prose>
</BaseLayout>
